-- South African Stocks Rise to Three-Week High, Led by Anglo Platinum, CIC
-- Carli Lourens
-- 2010-07-13T15:56:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-13/south-african-stocks-rise-to-three-week-high-led-by-anglo-platinum-cic.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose 303.63, or 1.1 percent, to 27,495.94 in
Johannesburg, its highest close since June 23.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ) had its biggest gain in a
week, climbing 15.99 rand, or 2.2 percent, to 736.50 rand. The
world’s biggest platinum producer said first-half profit rose as
much as 15 percent from a year earlier as metal prices climbed.
 Anglo American Plc , which owns about 80 percent of Anglo
Platinum, rose 3.49 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 278.87 rand.  
 CIC Holdings Ltd.  (CCI SJ), the Namibian retail-service
group, rallied the most in almost two months, rising 25 cents,
or 10 percent, to 2.75 rand. Imperial Holdings Ltd. offered to
buy CIC for 723.8 million rand ($96 million).  
 Shoprite Holdings Ltd.  (SHP SJ) had its biggest gain in a
week, climbing 2 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 88.50 rand. South
Africa’s biggest retailer by market value, and  Pick n Pay Stores
Ltd.  (PIK SJ) were rated “buy” in new coverage at Avior
Research Ltd. on the outlook for margin growth and inflation.
Pick ‘n Pay gained 50 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 44 rand, the
biggest gain since July 1.  
 Telkom South Africa Ltd.  (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-
line phone company, fell 1.18 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 33.56
rand, the lowest price in four months. Chief Financial Officer
Peter Nelson will resign in October, the company said, without
giving a reason.  
